summary.seg: The manuscript contains an anonymous Church History (Historia Ecclesiastica) traditionally attributed, on the basis of a mention by patriarch Photius in his Bibliotheca, to Gelasius of Cyzicus ( see Hansen 2002, pp. ix-xii). The work, in three books, consists mainly of a collection of Acts of the Nicene Council (325 CE).

The manuscript was copied from MS Cambridge, Trinity College, B.3.18
( Hansen 2002, p. xxvi) of the 16th century. Hansen has pointed out that a Latin translation of the work by Clint Kitchingman made on the basis of this Caius manuscript is contained in MSS Cambridge, Clare College Library, 28 and London, British Library, Cotton Nero D.10(1) (see Hansen 2002, p. xxvi).

msItem.rubric: f. [1]r Σύνταγμα τῶν κατὰ τὴν ἐν Νικαίᾳ ἁγίαν σύνοδον πραχθέντων
msItem.incipit: f. [1]r Τὰ κατὰ τὴν ἁγίαν καὶ μεγάλην καὶ οἰκουμενικὴν τῶν ἐπισκόπων
msItem.explicit: f. [100]v ὁ θεός σε διαφυλάξει, ἀδελφὲ ἀγαπητέ
msItem.note: This anonymous text has been traditionally attributed to Gelasius of Cyzicus (5th c.) Gelasius, of Cyzicus, active 475 , see G.C. Hansen, Anonyme Kirchengeschichte (Gelasius Cyzicenus, CPG 6034), Berlin 2002, pp. IX-XII

support.material: ff. [1]-[100] Western paper, folded in folio. Watermarks: Shield with an undefined motif on it ( ca. 25 20 ) in the centre of the leaf, no exact parallels have been found in the main repertoires, due to the scarce visibility of the watermark's particulars.

collation.p: The manuscript consists mainly of quaternions.
collation.signatures: Signatures constituted by letters of the Latin alphabet, in a brown ink, are visible in the lower margin, recto, of the first leaf of the quires, from b ( f. [9]r) to n ( f. [95]r). The ink has faded, they are not always clearly readable.
collation.catchwords: Horizontal catchwords by the scribes in the lower margin, right, right below the text, on each leaf recto and verso.

supportDesc.condition: The manuscript is in fair condition. The binding is very stained. The leaves have not been trimmed regularly.

additions.p: In the upper margin, left, of f. [1]r is pasted a paper label with manuscript notes about the manuscript's acquisition, Sothebys Lot. 1409 | 1/2/73 Gelasius of Cyzicum ? | Acts of the Nicene Council (in Greek), and a paper strip with printed notes (from Sotheby's sale as well), 1409 Nicaeensis Concilii Acta, Graece, Manuscript, Saec. XVI.

binding.p:
Early modern soft parchment binding. Titles written in ink on the left board, Account of the Council of Nicaea, and on the spine, Concilium Nicaenum Graece; on the spine, in the upper part, is written the number 2; on it, moreover, are pasted two papaer labels with the two shelfmarks 791 (in red) and 788.
400 270 ca. 25
binding.condition: The cover is torn at the edges and stained. There are worm holes on the right board.

accMat.p: On the left board and on the right board are pasted two parchment leaves of a 15th c. copy of Lyra on the Epistles.

origin.p: The manuscript was copied by three contemporary hands between the second half of the 16th c. and the beginning of the 17th : the manuscript was copied from MS Cambridge, Trinity College, B.3.18, copied around the middle of the 16th c., and was used for a Latin translation contained in two manuscripts of the 17th c., before 1663 ( Hansen 2002, p. xxvi).

provenance.p: The manuscript was sold at Sotheby's on 1st February 1873 (lot 1409, see Additions). It was owned by the English Biblical scholar Henry Barclay Swete (1835-1917) Swete, Henry Barclay, 1835-1917 . In the lower margin of f. [1]r is pasted a bookplate with his name and the date of 1890.

history.acquisition: The manuscript was donated to the College by Henry Barclay Swete Swete, Henry Barclay, 1835-1917 . In the lower margin of f. [1]r is pasted the Gonville and Caius College bookplate.

recordHist.source: Description (2021) draws partly on M. R. James, Supplement to the catalogue of manuscripts in the library of Gonville and Caius College, Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, 1914, p. 39.
